e not something the school system should be teaching. I walk into class expecting to learn the steps of mitosis and how to simplify radical expressions; not to have a deity I believe to be false thrown at my face. It wouldn’t be bothersome if a group of students got together and collectively said a prayer, so long as it doesn’t disrupt class-time (so it takes place during homeroom or between classes) and isn’t loud or being forced on others. It’s when it goes from voluntary to mandatory that prayer in school becomes a problem. Even if students are given the choice to opt out, it’s not fair to call them out on their beliefs like that. &#10;Regardless of what the majority of Americans believe in, there are minorities who view things differently. Is it really so hard to show them and their beliefs some respect by not indoctrinating them with your own? "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1160" language="en" documentId="1761" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Kippy" date="12/15/2010 09:46 PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.forerunner.com/forerunner/X0098_Ban_on_school_prayer.html#c002107" topic="prayer-in-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="1761" notes="" title="Banning Prayer in Public Schools Has Led to America's Demise"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="293"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="294" end="945"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="946" end="1160"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47"/></xmi:XMI>